I have gotten my data from the City of New Yorks data website. This is their shooting incident data, as recorded from 2006 all the way until the end of 2020.

It contains quite a lot of information, such as some information about the perpetrator and the victim. There are fields for the race, age group, and sex of both victims and perpetrators. It also includes whether the victim was murdered.

It also includes location information about each shooting, even up to latitude and longitude! It even includes a description of the location, as well as the precinct and jurisdiction code of each location where the shootings take place.

Of course, it also includes the time and date of each shooting.

incidents <-incidents %>%
  mutate(OCCUR_DATE = mdy(OCCUR_DATE),  # convert OCCUR_DATE to date
         BORO = factor(BORO),
         LOCATION_DESC = factor(LOCATION_DESC),
         STATISTICAL_MURDER_FLAG = factor(STATISTICAL_MURDER_FLAG),
         PERP_AGE_GROUP = factor(PERP_AGE_GROUP),
         PERP_SEX = factor(PERP_SEX),
         PERP_RACE = factor(PERP_RACE),
         VIC_AGE_GROUP = factor(VIC_AGE_GROUP),
         VIC_SEX = factor(VIC_SEX),
         VIC_RACE = factor(VIC_RACE)) %>%
  # remove unneeded columns
  select(-c(INCIDENT_KEY, PRECINCT, JURISDICTION_CODE,
            X_COORD_CD, Y_COORD_CD, Latitude, Longitude, Lon_Lat)) %>%
  # replace the NA entries as "unknown" or some variation
  replace_na(list(LOCATION_DESC="NONE",
                  PERP_AGE_GROUP="UNKNOWN",
                  PERP_SEX="U",
                  PERP_RACE="UNKNOWN"))

There are fields where the entries are blank. Examples include:

  • LOCATION_DESC
  • PERP_AGE_GROUP
  • PERP_SEX
  • PERP_RACE

What I did was to change the blank entries to reflect the same value used to denote an unknown value.

# sort by date
incidents <- incidents %>%
  arrange(OCCUR_DATE)

# use month instead of specific day
incidents <- incidents %>%
  mutate(Occur_Month = floor_date(OCCUR_DATE, "month"))

incidents$rec <- 1

# create a column for cumulative shootings by borough
with_cumulative_cases <- incidents %>%
  group_by(BORO) %>%
  mutate(Cumulative_Shootings = cumsum(rec)) %>%
  select(-rec) %>%
  ungroup()

# get the number of cumulative shootings per month by borough
with_cumulative_cases <- with_cumulative_cases %>%
  group_by(Occur_Month, BORO) %>%
  top_n(1, Cumulative_Shootings) %>%
  select(c(Occur_Month, BORO, Cumulative_Shootings)) %>%
  ungroup()

# divide the cases by borough
queens <- with_cumulative_cases %>%
  filter(BORO == "QUEENS")

manhattan <- with_cumulative_cases %>%
  filter(BORO == "MANHATTAN")

brooklyn <- with_cumulative_cases %>%
  filter(BORO == "BROOKLYN")

bronx <- with_cumulative_cases %>%
  filter(BORO == "BRONX")

staten_island <- with_cumulative_cases %>%
  filter(BORO == "STATEN ISLAND")

Here, I tried grouping the shootings by borough. I also realized that I didnt quite need information about the victim and the perpetrator, so I simply removed their columns.

queens %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Occur_Month, y = Cumulative_Shootings)) +
  geom_line(aes(color="Queens")) +
  geom_point(aes(color="Queens")) +
  
  geom_line(data=manhattan, aes(color="Manhattan")) +
  geom_point(data=manhattan, aes(color="Manhattan")) +
  
  geom_line(data=brooklyn, aes(color="Brooklyn")) +
  geom_point(data=brooklyn, aes(color="Brooklyn")) +
  
  geom_line(data=bronx, aes(color="Bronx")) +
  geom_point(data=bronx, aes(color="Bronx")) +
  
  geom_line(data=staten_island, aes(color="Staten Island")) +
  geom_point(data=staten_island, aes(color="Staten Island")) +
  
  scale_y_log10() +
  theme(legend.position="bottom",
        axis.text.x = element_text(angle=90)) +
  labs(title="Total Shootings in New York by Borough",
       y="Total shootings",
       x="Month")

The graphs show that Bronx and Brooklyn are the places with the most number of shooting incidents while Staten Island has the least number of shooting incidents. It has led me to ask if Bronx and Brooklyn truly are the most dangerous places in New York and if Staten Island is the safest place in New York.

# add new shootings column

queens <- queens %>%
  mutate(New_Shootings = Cumulative_Shootings - lag(Cumulative_Shootings))
queens$New_Shootings <- ifelse(is.na(queens$New_Shootings), 
                               queens$Cumulative_Shootings,
                               queens$New_Shootings)

manhattan <- manhattan %>%
  mutate(New_Shootings = Cumulative_Shootings - lag(Cumulative_Shootings))
manhattan$New_Shootings <- ifelse(is.na(manhattan$New_Shootings), 
                               manhattan$Cumulative_Shootings,
                               manhattan$New_Shootings)

brooklyn <- brooklyn %>%

                               staten_island$Cumulative_Shootings,
                               staten_island$New_Shootings)

Here, I added a new column for new shootings. I also made sure that there were no empty fields. I noticed that the first entry was empty because there was no value for lag(Cumulative_Shootings) at that point. For this, I simply copied over the Cumulative_Shootings value for the first month.

queens %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Occur_Month, y = New_Shootings)) +
  geom_line(aes(color="Queens")) +
  geom_point(aes(color="Queens")) +
  
  geom_line(data=manhattan, aes(color="Manhattan")) +
  geom_point(data=manhattan, aes(color="Manhattan")) +
  
  geom_line(data=brooklyn, aes(color="Brooklyn")) +
  geom_point(data=brooklyn, aes(color="Brooklyn")) +
  
  geom_line(data=bronx, aes(color="Bronx")) +
  geom_point(data=bronx, aes(color="Bronx")) +
  
  geom_line(data=staten_island, aes(color="Staten Island")) +
  geom_point(data=staten_island, aes(color="Staten Island")) +
  
  theme(legend.position="bottom",
       axis.text.x = element_text(angle=90)) +
  labs(title="New Monthly Shootings in New York by Borough",
       y="New Monthly Shootings",
       x="Month")

According to this graph, there appear to be several sharp spikes in shooting incidents in Brooklyn and Bronx. The other three boroughs, Manhattan, Queens, and Staten Island, appear to be more muted by comparison.

However, there is an even higher surge in shooting incidents in 2020. This increase is particularly sharp in Brooklyn and Bronx. What caused this spike? This sharp increase is unprecedented, especially in Brooklyn.

# queens monthly model
mod_queens <- lm(New_Shootings ~ Occur_Month, data=queens)
summary(mod_queens)

I try to make a linear model for each of the boroughs.

A linear model isnt particularly accurate when trying to predict the number of shootings per month. How would our graphs look like when we use yearly data instead?

# queens
queens_by_year <- queens %>%
  mutate(Occur_Year = floor_date(Occur_Month, "year"))

queens_by_year <- queens_by_year %>%
  group_by(Occur_Year, BORO) %>%
  top_n(1, Cumulative_Shootings) %>%
  select(c(Occur_Year, BORO, Cumulative_Shootings)) %>%
  ungroup()

queens_by_year <- queens_by_year %>%
  mutate(Cumulative_Shootings_By_Year = Cumulative_Shootings)

queens_by_year <- queens_by_year %>%
  mutate(New_Shootings_By_Year = Cumulative_Shootings_By_Year - lag(Cumulative_Shootings_By_Year))
queens_by_year$New_Shootings_By_Year <- ifelse(is.na(queens_by_year$New_Shootings_By_Year), 
                                               queens_by_year$Cumulative_Shootings_By_Year,
                                               queens_by_year$New_Shootings_By_Year)

  group_by(Occur_Year, BORO) %>%
  top_n(1, Cumulative_Shootings) %>%
  select(c(Occur_Year, BORO, Cumulative_Shootings)) %>%
  ungroup()

staten_island_by_year <- staten_island_by_year %>%
  mutate(Cumulative_Shootings_By_Year = Cumulative_Shootings)

staten_island_by_year <- staten_island_by_year %>%
  mutate(New_Shootings_By_Year = Cumulative_Shootings_By_Year - lag(Cumulative_Shootings_By_Year))
staten_island_by_year$New_Shootings_By_Year <- ifelse(is.na(staten_island_by_year$New_Shootings_By_Year), 
                                                      staten_island_by_year$Cumulative_Shootings_By_Year,
                                                      staten_island_by_year$New_Shootings_By_Year)

Here, I grouped the data by year instead of month. I also created a new column for new shootings by year.

Linear models can now better fit the yearly data. This leads me to believe that there are some signals that vary by month rather than by year.

Conclusion

It appears that there is a general downward trend in the number of shootings in New York City. However, there is a sudden increase in the number of shootings in 2020.

It appears that Brooklyn is the borough with the highest number of shootings. Bronx comes in second. Queens has come in third, but its record is much closer to that of Manhattan, which came in fourth. Staten Island has come in last for the number of shootings, which makes it sound like a good place to live in.

I have heard that New York City had a dark side through scandals from the news. I might have heard of some hearsay, like through rap songs, that Queens and Bronx might not be the safest places. I tried to give things a fair shake by trying to visualize how things truly were like, according to the data. I was surprised that Brooklyn took the top spot instead, although Bronx took second.

I have also heard that crime could be disproportionately distributed along racial lines. One way I thought about addressing this is to focus on the number of shooting incidents according to borough, ignoring the racial information about the perpetrators and victims alike.
